com.inqwell.any.channel

Class AnyChannel

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.inqwell.any.AbstractAny
      • com.inqwell.any.channel.AnyChannel
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Any, InputChannel, OutputChannel, Serializable, Cloneable

    public class AnyChannel
extends AbstractAny
implements InputChannel, OutputChannel, Cloneable
    This class implements Inq's InputChannel and OutputChannel interfaces. It offers synchronisation between reader and writer threads of the channel whose physical transport is determined by the given ChannelDriver. Readers and writers rendevous at empty/full channels, although what constitutes full and empty depends on the driver implementation also.

    Read operations on this channel may be handled by a separate thread started within this channel for those cases where the ultimate receiver has multiple input sources and there is no thread provided by the Java runtime to deliver them. Anything read by this thread is then forwarded to the specified channel for eventual consumption. In addition, if a channel is so created there is no need to maintain a reference to it externally as it becomes 'owned' by the internal reader thread.

      • AnyChannel

        public AnyChannel(Socket s,
                  OutputChannel forwardTo,
                  boolean blockOnFull)
        Make a channel around the given driver with optional block on full. A separate thread will be started to perform read() operations from this channel and forward them to that specified. Thus, it doesn't make sense for the consumer (or any other) thread to do read()s on this channel, rather they perform their read()s on forwardTo.

        This facility supports a single read point for the ultimate consumer thread where the data source is not already provided with a thread by Java runtime. For example, data received at an RMI remote object or from the AWT is handled by a system thread, but data at a socket must be read by the consumer.

      • close

        public void close()
           throws AnyException
        Description copied from interface: InputChannel
        Close this channel. The following semantics apply:
        • Any data still waiting to be read from the channel remains available and will be returned by subsequent calls to read().
        • Once the channel has been emptied subsequent calls to read() generate a ChannelClosedException.
        • Whether or not the channel contains data, any subsequent calls to write() generate a WriteClosedChannelException.
        Note: this method is also defined on the interface OuputChannel. Either readers or writers can close a channel with the same results.
        Specified by:
        close in interface InputChannel
        Specified by:
        close in interface OutputChannel
        Throws:
        AnyException
